  <static seed="1203" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/MultiplyingRationals/MultiplyingRationals2.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{2}-4x}{x^{2}-4}} \div {\frac{x^{2}-16}{x^{2}-5x+6}}={}}</m><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{x\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+2\right)}, x\ne 4\hbox{ and }x\ne 2\hbox{ and }x\ne 3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{2}-4x}{x^{2}-4}} \div {\frac{x^{2}-16}{x^{2}-5x+6}} 
      \amp = \frac{{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}}{{\left(x-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+2\right)}} \div \frac{{\left(x-4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+4\right)}}{{\left(x-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}} \\
      \amp = \frac{{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}}{{\left(x-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+2\right)}} \cdot \frac{{\left(x-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}}{{\left(x-4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+4\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+2\right)}, x\ne 4\hbox{ and }x\ne 2\hbox{ and }x\ne 3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>x - 4</m> and <m>x - 2</m> were canceled, <m>x \ne 4</m> and <m>x \ne 2</m> are lost domain conditions.</p>
<p>Note that <m>x - 3</m> used to be in the denominator, but not any more in the solution. This is why <m>x \ne 3</m> is also a lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
